How to re-dimension the Regression Tree:

9.3.a.iii

we consider the question in the errata corrige version of the book, the question is as follows: “How might we achieve better validation predictive performance at the expense of the training performance?” source: https://www.dataminingbook.com/content/errata-r-edition

As said previously, our overall error to start with for the training data is not 0, this is implied by the book because of the required 100 tree levels in the starting model.

Theoretically, a fully grown tree over fits the data, meaning it models on all the peculiar noise of the specific training set we are considering, until the prediction error is 0. When the regression tree starts modelling/splitting noise of the training set, that is when the tree will start performing very badly on the validation data. There are 2 ways of avoiding this, stopping the growing of the tree or pruning the fully grown tree.

In the first case, you can control the growth of the regression tree through the complexity parameter, which would result difficult. Another option is pruning the tree. This means getting rid of those branches (splits) that do not reduce the error rate enough. It trades off the error rate in the validation set and the size of the tree, so to model the relationship between predictors and outcome variable but not the noise. (source:https://bookdown.org/mpfoley1973/data-sci/regression-tree.html)

The complexity parameter decreases by the amount of nodes generated, that is because partitions of the outcome variable gets purer and purer. Xerror is the cross validation error, the xstd is the standard deviation. Root node error is 11,836,229.

To prune the tree one should look at the smallest xerror. In this case, with this dataset, by doing this what we get is that the smallest xerror is the last one,the one belonging to the complete tree. This means that by choosing the corresponding Cp our pruned tree would look like exactly like the full grown tree.

plotcp(toyota_tree, upper = "splits") # we plot the progression of complexity values

In fact, if we plot the relationship between the cross-validation error and the complexity value, we see that it declines steadily.

To get the best pruned tree one should look at the lower number of splits within 1 standard error of the minimum xerror tree (figure 9.13 of the book). So the minimum xerror is 0.145530(at row 22, nsplits 23), its xstd is 0.0147281, we look for the simplest model with the a xerror below the value( within 1 std) 0.133358 + 0.0140827= 0.16.

0.145530 + 0.0147281
## [1] 0.1602581

The minimum cross-validation error within 1 standard deviation is 0.158521, at row 9 with 8 splits and the corresponding complexity value of 0.00441024. We compute our pruned tree for this Cp.

set.seed(1234)
pruned_toyota_tree<- prune(toyota_tree,cp =0.00441024) #we report the Cp we found before
rpart.plot(pruned_toyota_tree, yesno = TRUE, digits = -3) #plot the regression tree

length(pruned_toyota_tree$frame$var[pruned_toyota_tree$frame$var == "<leaf>"]) # how many end nodes
## [1] 10

Our Best Pruned Tree has 10 terminal nodes. The last split executed is the one for Powered Windows=0.

Performance of Binned Price tree

9.3.b.i

The terminal. We used the type class because by binning the price we are drawing a classification tree.The ranking of importance of variables has changed, CD_Player seems to have increased in importance, which is quite odd. Comparison:

9.3.b.ii & iii

So in the classification tree case, our price prediction is going to be categorical, so based on the predictors, the new record will be classified as belonging to one of the 20 price levels. For the case in which we “drop” the new record down the regression tree, we are going to get an estimate of what the price for that used car is.

#we introduce the new records
options(scipen = 999, digits = 3)
corolla_nr<- data.frame (Age_08_04 = 77,KM = 117000,HP = 110,Automatic = 0,Doors = 5,Quarterly_Tax = 100,Mfr_Guarantee = 0,Guarantee_Period = 3,Airco = 1,Automatic_airco = 0,CD_Player = 0,Powered_Windows = 0, Sport_Model = 0,Tow_Bar = 1,Fuel_Type="Petrol")
# we introduce the new record

corolla_prediction_t1<- predict(smaller_tree, newdata = corolla_nr, method = "anova") #we predict on the default values tree
corolla_prediction_t2<- predict(binned_tree, newdata = corolla_nr, method="class") #we predict on the binned price tree
corolla_prediction_t3 <- predict(pruned_toyota_tree, newdata = corolla_nr, method= "anova") # we predict on the best pruned tree

The smaller tree and the pruned one predict the same Price for the new car. For the classification tree, the highest probability is for the new record being classified within interval 3.

The classification model does not seem to be the optimal choice, whilst for the other two models we are getting the same estimates. Yet we know that the Smaller Tree had bigger errors than the Best Pruned Tree. Yet The latter had more variation within its errors. All, the RMSE values we encountered (apart from the RMSE on the training set for the fully grown tree) were larger than the mean value ($10,613).

Because the splits are done one at the time, the trees might miss out on some relationship within the predictors, in fact we saw how th ebinning of the outcome variable brought up in importance a variable that did not seem relevant in previous models.
